WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.030 --> 00:00:03.970
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington, DC.

00:00:19.040 --> 00:00:22.740
&gt;&gt; John Cole: Good afternoon and
welcome to the Library of Congress

00:00:22.740 --> 00:00:25.080
and to our Books and
Beyond presentation.

00:00:25.080 --> 00:00:29.040
My name is John Cole, I'm the
director of the Center for the Book

00:00:29.040 --> 00:00:31.960
in the Library of Congress,
which is the reading

00:00:31.960 --> 00:00:34.650
and literacy promotion arm.

00:00:34.650 --> 00:00:39.990
It was created way back
in 1977 by Daniel Boorstin

00:00:39.990 --> 00:00:43.290
when he was librarian of
Congress who thought the Library

00:00:43.290 --> 00:00:47.560
of Congress should be doing more
to promote books and reading.

00:00:47.560 --> 00:00:53.240
And this was before even the word
literacy was well-known or used.

00:00:53.240 --> 00:00:59.190
And of course, when literacy became
a need in our society and something

00:00:59.190 --> 00:01:01.750
to be promoted it was
natural that the Center

00:01:01.750 --> 00:01:04.250
for the Book take that on.

00:01:04.250 --> 00:01:06.960
Today, we are the administrators
of the Library

00:01:06.960 --> 00:01:11.480
of Congress Literacy Awards
Project and we're also involved

00:01:11.480 --> 00:01:14.630
with other things at
a national level,

00:01:14.630 --> 00:01:16.730
in particular the National
Book Festival.

00:01:16.730 --> 00:01:21.030
And I hope that many of you know
about the National Book Festival.

00:01:21.030 --> 00:01:25.020
I brought this program from last
year's festival to remind me

00:01:25.020 --> 00:01:31.650
to give it a plug and also to
say that with the author program

00:01:31.650 --> 00:01:34.790
of the National Book Festival,
which has been the responsibility

00:01:34.790 --> 00:01:39.250
of the Center for the Book, along
with a pavilion of the states

00:01:39.250 --> 00:01:43.330
which has people coming
from all over the country

00:01:43.330 --> 00:01:45.370
to talk about books and reading.

00:01:45.370 --> 00:01:47.110
It was through the Book Festival

00:01:47.110 --> 00:01:51.530
that we've started getting more
interested in graphic novels.

00:01:51.530 --> 00:01:54.050 position:56%
And last year we really had quite --

00:01:54.050 --> 00:01:58.550
well last two years we've
really had quite a program.

00:01:58.550 --> 00:02:02.440
We do have a network of state
centers across the country

00:02:02.440 --> 00:02:04.470
in every state that
help promote books,

00:02:04.470 --> 00:02:07.100
reading, literacy and libraries.

00:02:07.100 --> 00:02:10.910
And we also work with
nonprofit organizations.

00:02:10.910 --> 00:02:16.240
Here at the Library of Congress
we feature talks such as this one

00:02:16.240 --> 00:02:22.100
at our noontime Books and Beyond
which feature new books by authors

00:02:22.100 --> 00:02:26.020 position:56%
who are connected one way or another
with the Library of Congress,

00:02:26.020 --> 00:02:31.060
often working as is this case with
today's speaker with our Prints

00:02:31.060 --> 00:02:33.890
and Photographs Division
quite closely.

00:02:33.890 --> 00:02:39.470
Our talks are all filmed
for later viewing

00:02:39.470 --> 00:02:42.970
on the Library of Congress website.

00:02:42.970 --> 00:02:47.340
So I'm asking you to please
turn off all things electronic.

00:02:47.340 --> 00:02:51.120 position:56%
I want to remind you of a couple of
handouts that are on the back table.

00:02:51.120 --> 00:02:55.500
We have a schedule of
future talks in this series.

00:02:55.500 --> 00:02:58.840
We also have the latest
issue of the Library

00:02:58.840 --> 00:03:04.270
of Congress magazine
imaginatively called LCM,

00:03:04.270 --> 00:03:09.210
which features the activities
of the Center for the Book.

00:03:09.210 --> 00:03:12.790
And we also have a form we'd
appreciate that you would fill

00:03:12.790 --> 00:03:17.970 position:56%
out telling us how you first learned
about this program to help us keep

00:03:17.970 --> 00:03:26.220
up the momentum of having from 12
to 20 of these talks each year.

00:03:26.220 --> 00:03:31.870
However, today to introduce --
the plan would be for our speaker

00:03:31.870 --> 00:03:37.730
to give a presentation, to make
a brief pause for any questions

00:03:37.730 --> 00:03:40.680
and answers and then there
will be a book signing

00:03:40.680 --> 00:03:43.880
at the conclusion right
here in this room.

00:03:43.880 --> 00:03:48.230
So welcome again and I would
like to welcome Martha Kennedy,

00:03:48.230 --> 00:03:51.820
a curator from the Prints
and Photographs Division,

00:03:51.820 --> 00:03:54.260
to introduce our program.

00:03:54.260 --> 00:03:58.120
And I'm also going to try to find
out from Martha what she is curator

00:03:58.120 --> 00:04:00.490
of since I never seem
to get it right.

00:04:00.490 --> 00:04:04.710
Would you like to include that
in your self-introduction Martha?

00:04:04.710 --> 00:04:06.510
Thank you.

00:04:06.510 --> 00:04:11.030
[ Applause ]

00:04:11.030 --> 00:04:14.230
&gt;&gt; Martha Kennedy: Thank
you very much John.

00:04:14.230 --> 00:04:17.290
Good afternoon, welcome.

00:04:17.290 --> 00:04:21.030
My name is Martha Kennedy
and I'm a curator of popular

00:04:21.030 --> 00:04:24.360
and applied graphic art
here at the library.

00:04:24.360 --> 00:04:28.640
And we -- that means I have
the great privilege of working

00:04:28.640 --> 00:04:31.830
with original cartoon and comic art

00:04:31.830 --> 00:04:35.120
and illustration art,
among other materials.

00:04:35.120 --> 00:04:40.060
We are very thrilled in the
Prints and Photographs Division

00:04:40.060 --> 00:04:43.890
to be cosponsoring this program
with the Center for the Book today.

00:04:43.890 --> 00:04:48.370
And it's an honor for me to
introduce our speaker, Peter Kuper,

00:04:48.370 --> 00:04:52.060
the author, artist of
the graphic novel Ruins.

00:04:52.060 --> 00:04:56.400 position:56%
Peter is an award-winning cartoonist
and illustrator and editor,

00:04:56.400 --> 00:04:59.290
art director and arts educator.

00:04:59.290 --> 00:05:03.390
He is a very versatile
and prolific artist.

00:05:03.390 --> 00:05:08.110
He creates not only cartoons
and comics, graphic novels,

00:05:08.110 --> 00:05:13.350 position:56%
but also illustrations and cover art
for major magazines and newspapers.

00:05:13.350 --> 00:05:19.210
Currently he is all a visiting
professor at Harvard University.

00:05:19.210 --> 00:05:23.150
Peter was born in Summit, New
Jersey, grew up in Cleveland, Ohio,

00:05:23.150 --> 00:05:28.120 position:56%
attended Kent State University, then
came to New York City and studied

00:05:28.120 --> 00:05:30.840
at the Art Students League
and the Pratt Institute.

00:05:30.840 --> 00:05:35.900
Oh dear, I messed something up.

00:05:35.900 --> 00:05:39.660
He and his friend and
fellow cartoonist,

00:05:39.660 --> 00:05:45.500 position:56%
Seth Tobocman cofounded the Politics
Graphics magazine World War 3

00:05:45.500 --> 00:05:50.970
illustrated in 1979 and
it is still going strong.

00:05:50.970 --> 00:05:54.210
Peter is well-known for writing
and drawing Mad Magazine Spy

00:05:54.210 --> 00:05:58.190
Versus Spy also for
more than 18 years now.

00:05:58.190 --> 00:06:00.970
He's created more than
a dozen graphic novels,

00:06:00.970 --> 00:06:04.120
including The System,
Sticks and Stones,

00:06:04.120 --> 00:06:08.300
Adaptation to Franz Kafka's The
Metamorphosis and Give It Up,

00:06:08.300 --> 00:06:11.860
and a wonderful
semi-autobiographical graphic novel

00:06:11.860 --> 00:06:15.250
called Stop Forgetting to Remember.

00:06:15.250 --> 00:06:18.240
Peter received a journalism
award from the Society

00:06:18.240 --> 00:06:25.130
of Newspaper Designers in 2001,
two gold medals and a silver medal

00:06:25.130 --> 00:06:29.290
from the Society of
Illustrators in New York City.

00:06:29.290 --> 00:06:32.960
His work has been published
and exhibited internationally

00:06:32.960 --> 00:06:37.060
and the library is fortunate
to hold examples of his strong

00:06:37.060 --> 00:06:41.660
and vivid drawings and prints in
Prints and Photographs Division.

00:06:41.660 --> 00:06:45.070
He remains remarkably modest in
light of his many accomplishments

00:06:45.070 --> 00:06:47.250
about which more could be said,

00:06:47.250 --> 00:06:51.510
but for the moment please help me
welcome Peter Kuper, thank you.

00:06:51.510 --> 00:06:55.500
[ Applause ]

00:07:00.040 --> 00:07:01.340
&gt;&gt; Peter Kuper: I followed
that fight up to the part

00:07:01.340 --> 00:07:03.390
where you said delightfully
modest and I thought

00:07:03.390 --> 00:07:05.130
that doesn't sound familiar.

00:07:05.130 --> 00:07:11.980
So thank you so much for coming
and thank you to the library

00:07:11.980 --> 00:07:15.930
for having me, it's
really an honor to be here.

00:07:15.930 --> 00:07:20.330 position:56%
And we first connected back in 2001,

00:07:20.330 --> 00:07:26.320
after 9/11 when there was an art
show in New York that had a number

00:07:26.320 --> 00:07:31.640
of pieces that were about 9/11
and I was really grateful to make

00:07:31.640 --> 00:07:35.650
that connection and stay in
touch throughout the years.

00:07:35.650 --> 00:07:40.190
So I'm going to give you
a little bit of history

00:07:40.190 --> 00:07:44.700
and I hope you'll follow along with
me and I won't bore you to death.

00:07:44.700 --> 00:07:49.420
So some of my history or
maybe all of our history.

00:07:49.420 --> 00:07:56.600
I grew up in the 60's and
was sort of at the tail end

00:07:56.600 --> 00:08:00.080
of experiencing the Vietnam
War and the hippie movement

00:08:00.080 --> 00:08:03.230
and all these things that I
really felt like I missed out on

00:08:03.230 --> 00:08:06.800
and not the war so much
as the hippie movement.

00:08:06.800 --> 00:08:14.800 position:56%
But there's this history that we all
seem to have that I get to capture

00:08:14.800 --> 00:08:17.830
in every issue of Mad
Magazine with Spy Versus Spy,

00:08:17.830 --> 00:08:21.860
our tendency towards
some form of destruction.

00:08:21.860 --> 00:08:27.710
And we've been capturing our
history in art and in fact,

00:08:27.710 --> 00:08:29.610
it's one of the few
things that remains

00:08:29.610 --> 00:08:31.790
to indicate where we came from.

00:08:31.790 --> 00:08:36.340
There's no music left unfortunately
from those days, those early days.

00:08:36.340 --> 00:08:41.570
And there has been a tendency --
there's our early shopping habits

00:08:41.570 --> 00:08:48.000
and that's actually Banksy he
put that up at the British Museum

00:08:48.000 --> 00:08:50.500
and it stayed up for a couple weeks
before anybody realized it wasn't

00:08:50.500 --> 00:08:52.240
part of the exhibit.

00:08:52.240 --> 00:08:54.180
Got to love Banksy.

00:08:54.180 --> 00:08:58.080
So one of the things that
has seemed to happen also is

00:08:58.080 --> 00:09:04.080
that artists are drawn to
talk about real life events.

00:09:04.080 --> 00:09:09.890
And somebody like Goya who to
his detriment did this series

00:09:09.890 --> 00:09:14.810
of etchings, Disasters of War,

00:09:14.810 --> 00:09:18.300
and paintings talking
about what was going on.

00:09:18.300 --> 00:09:20.810
And he was, you know, sort of the
court painter and he didn't have

00:09:20.810 --> 00:09:24.470
to be doing this and it
didn't help his career along.

00:09:24.470 --> 00:09:29.190
The same with Daumier who
his portrait of the King

00:09:29.190 --> 00:09:33.970
in France got him a
six-month jail time.

00:09:33.970 --> 00:09:39.340 position:56%
So there has been this aspect of art
that has always wanted to reach out

00:09:39.340 --> 00:09:42.670
and comment on the
pillars of society

00:09:42.670 --> 00:09:45.800
like Boss Tweed, this
is Thomas Nast.

00:09:45.800 --> 00:09:47.630
And famously his drawing

00:09:47.630 --> 00:09:53.420
of Boss Tweed helped
the customs identify him

00:09:53.420 --> 00:09:58.590
when Boss Tweed fled the country
having pretty much ransacked the

00:09:58.590 --> 00:10:05.330
treasury of New York and he ended
up dying penniless in jail, woohoo.

00:10:05.330 --> 00:10:08.100
Thomas Nast also developed
the elephant and the donkey

00:10:08.100 --> 00:10:11.310
as our Democratic and
Republican symbols.

00:10:11.310 --> 00:10:14.400
He also did the first
image of Santa Claus,

00:10:14.400 --> 00:10:19.460
but some very wise people felt that
a little more color would be nice

00:10:19.460 --> 00:10:21.500
and so the Coca-Cola Company,

00:10:21.500 --> 00:10:25.650
figuring that would be perfect
to work with their logo.

00:10:25.650 --> 00:10:28.730
That's why we have a red
and white Santa Claus.

00:10:28.730 --> 00:10:31.880
The English tried to change it
to green and white more recently

00:10:31.880 --> 00:10:36.670
and nobody was buying it,
Coke is just too popular.

00:10:36.670 --> 00:10:39.730
So there were magazines also
that were giving a forum

00:10:39.730 --> 00:10:44.090
to political artists like the
Masses and they too were shut

00:10:44.090 --> 00:10:48.390
down when Woodrow Wilson had
promised us not to go into war

00:10:48.390 --> 00:10:52.610
and then did and there was a whole
movement against work like this.

00:10:52.610 --> 00:10:56.980
This is the perfect
soldier by Robert Miner.

00:10:56.980 --> 00:11:01.590
And Simplicissimus in Germany
which gave a voice to artists

00:11:01.590 --> 00:11:06.190
like Kathe Kollwitz
and John Hartfield.

00:11:06.190 --> 00:11:09.280
And, you know, it threatened
their lives

00:11:09.280 --> 00:11:12.690
to do images like this in the 30's.

00:11:12.690 --> 00:11:17.660
George Gross, many of them, in
fact probably all them had to flee

00:11:17.660 --> 00:11:21.750
in order to avoid concentration
camps.

00:11:21.750 --> 00:11:26.810
Picasso got into the act too
with Guernica about the bombing

00:11:26.810 --> 00:11:32.570
of a Spanish town in Spain,
Spanish town in Spain.

00:11:32.570 --> 00:11:36.500
And Diego Rivera's a mural
Man at the Crossroads,

00:11:36.500 --> 00:11:39.560
which he curiously was hired
by Rockefeller to do it

00:11:39.560 --> 00:11:40.860
at the Rockefeller Center.

00:11:40.860 --> 00:11:42.160
And I don't know if
you know this story,

00:11:42.160 --> 00:11:46.950
but he put in this little
image of Lenin under the wing

00:11:46.950 --> 00:11:50.460
and Rockefeller said, you've
got to take out, you know,

00:11:50.460 --> 00:11:52.400
the biggest communist
is in the lobby

00:11:52.400 --> 00:11:54.470
of the biggest capitalist
you've got to take that out.

00:11:54.470 --> 00:11:57.230
And Diego, who is getting a
hard time from his friends

00:11:57.230 --> 00:12:02.620 position:56%
for having taken on this commission
said, no and so Rockefeller paid him

00:12:02.620 --> 00:12:06.220
and chiseled it off the wall.

00:12:06.220 --> 00:12:09.520
There he is working on
one mural or another.

00:12:09.520 --> 00:12:14.530 position:56%
So you know art is used in many
directions, it's not always antiwar.

00:12:14.530 --> 00:12:19.070
The government can use
it to direct people

00:12:19.070 --> 00:12:22.710
into war and/or to support the war.

00:12:22.710 --> 00:12:25.210
And, but then again there's
always some lefty popping

00:12:25.210 --> 00:12:31.200
up with their little
commentary on even that.

00:12:31.200 --> 00:12:34.580
So in the 50's there were war
comics that were being produced.

00:12:34.580 --> 00:12:37.720
Harvey Kurtzman was out one
of the editors who did this

00:12:37.720 --> 00:12:41.990
and he was really trying to do
comics that were for adults,

00:12:41.990 --> 00:12:44.990
for soldiers in fact
talking about war as it was.

00:12:44.990 --> 00:12:48.340
He was very concerned with being
accurate with all the armaments

00:12:48.340 --> 00:12:50.930
that no one could call him
out and say that, you know,

00:12:50.930 --> 00:12:55.260
it's a comic and, you know, it's
just sort of glossing over things.

00:12:55.260 --> 00:12:57.180
This was also coming
from a company EC

00:12:57.180 --> 00:13:02.330
that was doing pretty much a
whole series of amazing comics.

00:13:02.330 --> 00:13:05.610
But this was in the 50's
around the time of McCarthyism

00:13:05.610 --> 00:13:10.320
and there was a lot of scare
about well just everything,

00:13:10.320 --> 00:13:14.060
including the fear that comics
would lead to delinquency.

00:13:14.060 --> 00:13:20.280
And so there was a move by a guy
named Frederick Wertham he wrote an

00:13:20.280 --> 00:13:24.750
article that caused a big uproar,
the seduction of the innocent.

00:13:24.750 --> 00:13:28.120
And people decided that
comics were bad for children

00:13:28.120 --> 00:13:31.060
that violent comics
would lead to violence.

00:13:31.060 --> 00:13:33.000
We've heard this about
Dungeons and Dragons too,

00:13:33.000 --> 00:13:34.780
this is an ongoing story.

00:13:34.780 --> 00:13:38.430
And that led the industry to
say okay we'll self-censor,

00:13:38.430 --> 00:13:40.920
please don't kill us
we'll self-censor.

00:13:40.920 --> 00:13:45.290
And in that self-censoring with
the Comics Code they also agreed

00:13:45.290 --> 00:13:52.040 position:56%
to not have titles that included
words like weird and crypt and well,

00:13:52.040 --> 00:13:54.890
you know, pretty much
everything that EC published.

00:13:54.890 --> 00:13:57.290 position:56%
And that knocked that line of comics

00:13:57.290 --> 00:14:00.810
that was heading towards a whole
new possibility in the form

00:14:00.810 --> 00:14:05.790
of more adult comics, it
knocked it out and it ushered

00:14:05.790 --> 00:14:07.810
in superheroes in a big way.

00:14:07.810 --> 00:14:13.640
The only one standing from the
EC Company was oddly enough Mad

00:14:13.640 --> 00:14:15.830
Magazine, the most
subversive comic ever

00:14:15.830 --> 00:14:18.860
which shows you what happens
when you censor things.

00:14:18.860 --> 00:14:22.600
And Mad was a huge influence
on me, I grew up reading it

00:14:22.600 --> 00:14:25.720
and the idea that, you know,
you could say these things

00:14:25.720 --> 00:14:31.160
about the pillars of society
and make jokes and all.

00:14:31.160 --> 00:14:33.790
But I was a little put off
when they made fun of hippies

00:14:33.790 --> 00:14:37.120 position:56%
because I thought wait a minute like
where do they stand on these issues.

00:14:37.120 --> 00:14:42.120
I thought that they were left-wing
and then they were every wing.

00:14:42.120 --> 00:14:46.230
Around the same time
Jules Feiffer who's got --

00:14:46.230 --> 00:14:50.970
I believe his archives
are with the collection,

00:14:50.970 --> 00:14:54.130
brilliant cartoonist who's
done pretty much everything.

00:14:54.130 --> 00:14:59.030
Started to do a comic
strip in the Village Voice,

00:14:59.030 --> 00:15:03.620
along with having been drafted
in the Korean War he came

00:15:03.620 --> 00:15:06.770
up with the story of a boy
who's accidentally drafted,

00:15:06.770 --> 00:15:09.260
which is how he felt, a
four-year-old is drafted.

00:15:09.260 --> 00:15:14.390
And this made into an animated
film that won the Academy Award.

00:15:14.390 --> 00:15:17.590
Along comes Underground Comics
which is basically the children

00:15:17.590 --> 00:15:21.730
of Mad Magazine, Robert Crumb and
a number of people were coming

00:15:21.730 --> 00:15:25.920
out with comics that really, really
didn't have the Comics Code on them

00:15:25.920 --> 00:15:27.330
in any way, shape or form.

00:15:27.330 --> 00:15:29.970
But one of the things I noted
from these comics was also

00:15:29.970 --> 00:15:32.660
that they had a political sentiment
and the first things I heard

00:15:32.660 --> 00:15:38.490
about environmental movement
and a number of antiwar things

00:15:38.490 --> 00:15:41.500
in comics was coming
out of Underground.

00:15:41.500 --> 00:15:44.260
So this was a kind of poster
that you'd see on a lot

00:15:44.260 --> 00:15:46.330
of college walls in the late 60's.

00:15:46.330 --> 00:15:48.970
And I love the idea that
art could have this impact

00:15:48.970 --> 00:15:52.330
that people would put this out and
it was sort of like a rallying cry.

00:15:52.330 --> 00:15:54.870
And I grew up in the 70's
and it was, you know,

00:15:54.870 --> 00:15:58.290
I was hoping to do art and I
wished that I could do something

00:15:58.290 --> 00:16:00.690
that had a happier face on it.

00:16:00.690 --> 00:16:02.540
But somehow or another growing

00:16:02.540 --> 00:16:04.490
up through the Vietnam
War it was very difficult

00:16:04.490 --> 00:16:08.230
to ignore what was going
on behind that smile.

00:16:08.230 --> 00:16:13.200
And when I was in art school Ronald
Reagan was just coming into office.

00:16:13.200 --> 00:16:15.790
If you don't happen to
remember Ronald Reagan,

00:16:15.790 --> 00:16:19.230
it's okay he may not
have recalled either.

00:16:19.230 --> 00:16:23.930
But he promises a less
bureaucratic shadow government.

00:16:23.930 --> 00:16:28.310
That's The Onion, love The Onion.

